<b>Heaven forbid that I would forget this song! - </b>1/24/02 12:35:19 PM<br>~ <b>Devaney</b><blockquote>I routinely group with a cleric and rogue and we are a rather aggressive lot.  We tend to love non-stop pulling and fight a little close to spawn spots at times.  We have learned (the hard way) that Chain is one of the best songs to control a mob from running back to get reinforcments.  I constantly twist this song in my rotation to keep the mob from hitting so quickly and to &quot;chain&quot; it in place when it begins to run.  Mobs seldom resisit it and when they do, I simply break the cardinal rule of twisting (to keep going in your rotation) and recast the song.  Seldom does a mob resist it twice.<br><br>I love this song and on the few occassions I have forgotten to mem it, my cleric and rogues buddies glare at me in bewilderment.  The rogue loves the haste songs, the cleric is a mana song addict...and they BOTH scream for chain.  <br><br>Such devoted fans I have!!<br><br>Devaney<br>Bard of the 41st Song</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Key to soloing - </b>1/16/02 1:04:15 PM<br>~ <b>Steppy</b><blockquote>Soloing for bards means charm-kiting, fear-kiting, or dot-kiting.  In any case, this song is essential to success.  The snare effect is fundamental to making this sort of fighting work.  This WILL block a snare spell from taking hold, however so be careful in a group to coordinate with the group's snarers.  It does NOT stack with Largo's.  However, in a group with other snarers around, Largo's is probably the safer choice to avoid messing them up.</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Snaring Runners to save mana; Stacking issues - </b>1/14/02 1:44:08 PM<br>~ <b>Klapton</b><blockquote>I don't know if this stacks with root or Druid snares.  It should not be an issue if you inform your group that you will be snaring runners.  The only other time for rooting is an emergency get-the-mob-off-the-cleric type situation, in which case a true caster's root spell is best.<br><br>To snare runners, watch the targets health bar.  Depending on how quickly your group is taking them down, you may need to fire the song off sooner.  If you do it a little early, no harm is done, you miss one other song twist in that cycle, and can sing it again so it sticks.<br><br>Also regarding timing:  If the mobs are resistant, sing the song a tick or two earlier than you think you need to.  That way you can fire it off again if it resists, and usually you can stop the runner.<br><br>p.s:  If you are using AE songs especially, tell your druid that with the mana he saves not having to snare runners, he can cast a damage shield on you when you get multiples.  (Every mob except the one the tank is hacking will most likely be whomping on you!  Dmg shields are 100% non-resistable damage--gotta love it).<br><br>Klapton, lvl 25, Vaezelle</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Stacking - </b>12/26/01 7:29:48 PM<br>~ <b>Musicman</b><blockquote>If this song is on a mob, snare/ensnare will not take.  It no longer breaks snare/ensnare, if it is on the mob.  Therefore, if grouped with a Druid wait until after the mob is snared and then weave it in to the mix for the slow effect.<br><br><br>Musicman 42 Level bard</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
